post_text: Help us spread the word.....Now that KSHSAA has cleared the way, The Spartans will be having High School FB Camp from 7:30 PM to 9:30 PM on Monday/Tuesday/Wednesday/Thursday (August 3-6) in Dexter. As we prepare to start the season the next three weeks will look like this....Camp this week....off next week....practice begins the 17th at a time TBD.....With school getting out early last year there never was a chance to get sign-up sheets out and put together a mailing list, so we are doing the best we can to spread the word. Participants will not be allowed into the buildings (Bathroom Use Only) and need to bring there own water jug, water bottles will not be available due to COVID safety precautions. Coaxh Wachter will let all CV kids know safety protocols for the ride over and meet/leave times individually. Everyone coming on their own need to be dressed, (shorts/shirt/cleats) and on the field at 7:30 PM sharp ready to roll. No Pads/No Contact...Fundamnetals/Drills/Installation only this week as we acclimate back into things.

Good Afternoon! Just a reminder that enrollment will be held as scheduled on July, 28, 2020 from 8 to 8 or by appointment. The following was mailed home today to all returning students who were enrolled during the 2019-2020 school year. If you are new to the district please bring all vital information needed to enrollment including the students birth certificate. If you are a NEW enrollee from out of district we encourage you to arrive early, as those spots will be limited, and will be determined on a first come, first serve basis. If you cannot make it on this day please contact the office and request the necessary forms that need to be turned in. We look forward to having a great year and can not wait to get started again!

Update....as stated in the letter we will stay with an start day of September 9th.....This allows plenty of time to have Phase 1 of construction project completed üòâ. We will post and send an adjusted school calendar in the near future.

As always ‚ÄúIts‚Äôs a Great Day 2B a Cardinal!‚Äù

post_text: We R Full Speed Ahead üèé and things are BUZZING! Look at the original deck of the roof and those steel beams! These beams will be painted RED and the deck of the ceiling BLACK by Rob Carrol (local company) and left exposed for everyone to see üëç The Lampson brothers (local company) have kicked some tail on the interior demolition of this building removing the floor, ceiling, bleachers, conduit, block walls, etc....üëè so great to have local people involved with this project! The masons are doing great work on the interior/exterior of the building repairing cracks and worn down ascetics that have accrued over the first 73 years of this buildings life and preparing it for the next 73 years! The window removal in the front was done by some of our fabulous summer crew as they work to restore these amazing window cases/frames and prepare them to be re-glazed. This is a really cool part of the bond issue bringing this building back to life! ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs a Great Day 2B a Cardinal!‚Äù

It is with sadness the we are making this post, but feel someone might be able to help us handle this unfortunate situation.....if so please contact the HS Office at 620-876-5415.

The remodel of the current elementary school was broken into and vandalized sometime between 5:00 PM on Friday and 6:00 AM on Monday. Individual(s) did damage to the framing studs for the new walls. All of the framing studs will need to be taken down and replaced costing us valuable time and money. No items have been reported as stolen. There is a $1500 reward for information leading to the identification and arrest of the individual(s) who were involved in this isolated incident. There will considerations given for self admittance if the indiviudal(s) come forward and admit the actions.

post_text: It is with frustration that we post this message and inform all of you that the June 6, 2020 Graduation Date will need to be rescheduled to a future date of June 19th or later. The Graduation, even outdoors as we had planned, is considered an event that will exceed the limit of 45 people and is not prohibited before June 19th per the Governors latest guidance and orders. We have scheduled a Zoom meeting for this Friday with Senior parents to get their input on where we go from here in regards to future plans, reschdueling of the dates, etc....we are frustrated and feel terrible for those involved, but wish to work with them instead of just scheduling a future date sometime after the 19th of June and put our students and their families in a take it or leave it type of situation.

The moment we have anxiously been waiting for from The Governor has came and went.....with the most recent announcement and guidelines laid out before us we must now shift from contingency plan #1 to contingency plan #2 which we are currently working on. This plan will include our Graduating Seniors as well as our promoting 8th Graders....I know most of you are trying to plan things, therefore we are going to stay with the originally scheduled date, time and location. We will be in touch with all promoting 8th Graders and Seniors along with their families via text or voice message on Tuesday to reveal the plans for the day. We will continue to work tirelessly to make this a special day for these deserving students. Thank You for all of your patience.

post_text: The first of three pre-bid construction meetings...a lot of interest from contractors. Due to CDC recommendations we had to split it into three sessions. Over 16 General Contracting companies are represented today and have shown an interest in submitting bids, which well exceeded our expectations. Bids are due by 4:00 PM on April 21, 2020 and will be opened by the board at a special meeting at 7:00 PM on the 21st. Bids will be awarded and the remodel of the current elementary will begin on May 1, 2020 and is scheduled to be completed by July 25, 2020 in time for teachers to move in and be ready for the start of school on August 17, 2020.

post_text: The Functional Life Skills classroom continued Dexter's March civic activity today as they delivered homemade fudge from the Dexter Roost Roast, the local coffee shop ran by these students, to recognize and thank some of the special people within our community that help make their program a success. These students gain community, vocational and recreation and leisure life skills by mentoring and participating in job based skills within specific businesses that relate to their future transition work goals. These students would not be able to gain this very important instruction and training if we did not have the support of our local businesses. Our special thanks today goes out to Chop It up, Love Hair Fashions, Cowley County Humane Society, Pool‚Äôs body shop and Grouse Valley Grill. We also like to give special recognition to some of our favorite people at Cowley County Special Service Cooperative as we appreciate all that these individuals do for our students and staff! #ddawareness2020

post_text:
Roost Roast Coffee Shop Now Online
Need a quick and easy gift idea? Roost Roast Coffee Shop is now online and can be used to purchase punch cards for your student or even for yourself. To gain access to the Roost Roast punch cards, visit the usd471.org page and click on online payments located in the bottom right hand corner, followed by school store and finally Roost Roast Coffee Shop. All punch card options are located in the left hand column and can be viewed and ordered by clicking on the item of your choice. Punch cards currently come in increments of $10.00 for Bakery Items, $15.00 for Basic Beverages and $25.00 for Specialty drinks. There is also a holiday punch card option that allows you to determine a preferable amount for special occasions. Once the card is purchased, your student can come pick up their card in the Roost Roast at their convenience. This is a perfect way to treat the ones you love!

post_text: Dexter‚Äôs February civic activity called for a whole lot of lovin‚Äô as staff volunteers were asked to Pucker Up for a good cause! The February civic event was announced at the end of January and it was simply bovine! Jars for staff volunteers were placed in the cafeteria for two weeks as students, staff and community members were given the opportunity to fund the staff member of their choice for a smooch fest with Mrs. Champlin's calf during the homecoming assembly. It was announced that each dollar donated counted toward a vote for the staff member chosen and all the money raised from this activity would be used to fund random acts of kindness to the Dexter community. Thank you to the following staff members for volunteering your lips for this fun activity: Aaron Wise, Kelli Crain, Mandie Doak, Gina Anderson, Whitney Killman, Marla Martin, Erin Nichols and Darcie Randall. A little over $100 was raised and will be used to bring smiles to Dexter community members in the following months.
